Project Business Statistics: E-news Express¶

Define Problem Statement and Objectives¶

Business Context¶

The advent of e-news, or electronic news, portals has offered us a great opportunity to quickly get updates on the day-to-day events occurring globally. The information on these portals is retrieved electronically from online databases, processed using a variety of software, and then transmitted to the users. There are multiple advantages of transmitting new electronically, like faster access to the content and the ability to utilize different technologies such as audio, graphics, video, and other interactive elements that are either not being used or aren’t common yet in traditional newspapers.

E-news Express, an online news portal, aims to expand its business by acquiring new subscribers. With every visitor to the website taking certain actions based on their interest, the company plans to analyze these actions to understand user interests and determine how to drive better engagement. The executives at E-news Express are of the opinion that there has been a decline in new monthly subscribers compared to the past year because the current webpage is not designed well enough in terms of the outline & recommended content to keep customers engaged long enough to make a decision to subscribe.

A/B Testing¶

I will analyze user responses to two variants of a product to decide which of the two variants is more effective. This experimental technique, known as A/B testing, is used to determine whether a new feature attracts users based on a chosen metric.

Objective, Data Background, and Questions to Address¶

The design team of the company has researched and created a new landing page that has a new outline & more relevant content shown compared to the old page. In order to test the effectiveness of the new landing page in gathering new subscribers, the Data Science team conducted an experiment by randomly selecting 100 users and dividing them equally into two groups. The existing landing page was served to the first group (control group) and the new landing page to the second group (treatment group). Data regarding the interaction of users in both groups with the two versions of the landing page was collected.

I will explore the data and perform a statistical analysis (at a significance level of 5%) to determine the effectiveness of the new landing page in gathering new subscribers for the news portal by answering the following questions:

-Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than on the existing landing page?

-Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?

-Does the converted status depend on the preferred language?

-Is the time spent on the new page the same for the different language users?

Data Dictionary¶

The data contains information regarding the interaction of users in both groups with the two versions of the landing page.

user_id - Unique user ID of the person visiting the website

group - Whether the user belongs to the first group (control) or the second group (treatment)

landing_page - Whether the landing page is new or old

time_spent_on_the_page - Time (in minutes) spent by the user on the landing page

converted - Whether the user gets converted to a subscriber of the news portal or not

language_preferred - Language chosen by the user to view the landing page

1. Do the users spend more time on the new landing page than the existing landing page?¶

Perform Visual Analysis¶

In [148]:
# Visual Analysis of time spent on new vs old landing page
sns.boxplot(data=df, x='landing_page', y='time_spent_on_the_page', hue='landing_page')
Out[148]:
<Axes: xlabel='landing_page', ylabel='time_spent_on_the_page'>

Step 1: Define the null and alternate hypotheses¶

The null and alternative hypotheses can be formulated as:

$H_0$ : The mean time spent on the new landing page is less than or equal to the mean time spent on the old landing page.
$H_a$ : The mean time spent on the new landing page is greater than the old landing page.

Step 2: Select Appropriate test¶

We can compare the sample means from 2 independent populations when std devs are known, so we will use the 2-sample independant z-test.

Step 3: Decide the significance level¶

We will use a significance level of 0.05

Step 4: Collect and prepare data¶

In [149]:
#Divide the df based on landing page
new_df = df[df['landing_page'] == 'new']
old_df = df[df['landing_page'] == 'old']
In [150]:
# Show the old df statistical summary
old_df.describe().T
Out[150]:
count mean std min 25% 50% 75% max
user_id 50.0 546566.5000 17.677670 546493.00 546555.25 546567.50 546579.7500 546592.0
time_spent_on_the_page 50.0 4.5324 2.581975 0.19 2.72 4.38 6.4425 10.3

The average time spent on the existing page is 4.5 minutes

In [151]:
# Show new df statistical summary
new_df.describe().T
Out[151]:
count mean std min 25% 50% 75% max
user_id 50.0 546467.5000 14.577380 546443.00 546455.250 546467.500 546479.75 546492.00
time_spent_on_the_page 50.0 6.2232 1.817031 1.65 5.175 6.105 7.16 10.71

The average time spent on the new page is 6.22 minutes Over 75% of the sample spent more than 5 minutes on the page.

Step 5: Calculate the p-value¶

In [152]:
#Calculate the p value
t_statistic, p_value = stats.ttest_ind(new_df['time_spent_on_the_page'], old_df['time_spent_on_the_page'], alternative='greater')
print('P Value:', p_value)

P Value: 0.0001316123528095005

Step 6: Compare the p-value with $\alpha$¶

In [153]:
# print the conclusion based on p-value
if p_value < 0.05:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.')
else:
    print(f'As the p-value {p_value} is greater than the level of significance, we fail to reject the null hypothesis.')

As the p-value 0.0001316123528095005 is less than the level of significance, we reject the null hypothesis.

Step 7: Draw inference¶

At 5% significance level, we reject the null hypothesis. We have enough statistical evidence to say that the mean time spent on the new landing page is greater than the mean time spent on the old landing page.

A similar approach can be followed to answer the other questions.

2. Is the conversion rate (the proportion of users who visit the landing page and get converted) for the new page greater than the conversion rate for the old page?¶

In [154]:
# Color chart of old df conversion and new df conversion
sns.countplot(data=df, x='converted', hue='landing_page', legend=False)
Out[154]:
<Axes: xlabel='converted', ylabel='count'>

The null and alternative hypotheses can be formulated as:

$H_0$ : The conversion rate proportion of the new page is equal or less than the conversion rate proportion of the old page.
$H_a$ : The conversion rate proportion of the new page is greater than the conversion rate proportion of the old page.

We can use a one tailed, two proportion z test to compare the conversion rate of these two independant samples with known variance.

We will use a significance level of 0.05

We can calculate the conversion rate data for each sample (old and new)

new_df['converted'].value_counts()
Out[157]:
converted
yes    33
no     17
Name: count, dtype: int64
In [158]:
conversion_rate_new = 33/50
conversion_rate_new
Out[158]:
0.66

We will address these rates in our conclusion and recommendation.

Performing the test with the data:

In [159]:
# Perform a one tailed two proportion z-test for conversion_rate_old and
# conversion_rate_new
count = np.array([21, 33])
nobs = np.array([50, 50])
stat, pval = proportions_ztest(count, nobs)
print('P Value:', pval)

P Value: 0.016052616408112556

Our p value is less than the level of significance (0.05), so we will reject the null hypothesis.

In [160]:
# Printing our conclusion
print('At 5% significance level,')
if pval < 0.05:
  print('We reject the null hypothesis.')
  print('Yes, the conversion rate for the new page is significantly greater than the conversion rate for the old page.')
else:
  print('No, the conversion rate for the new page is not greater than the conversion rate for the old page.')

At 5% significance level,
We reject the null hypothesis.
Yes, the conversion rate for the new page is significantly greater than the conversion rate for the old page.

3. Is the conversion and preferred language are independent or related?¶

In [161]:
# Visual of conversion and preferred language
sns.countplot(data=df, x='language_preferred', hue='converted', legend=False)
Out[161]:
<Axes: xlabel='language_preferred', ylabel='count'>

$H_0$ : Conversion rate proportion and preferred language are independent.
$H_a$ : Conversion rate and preferred language are associated.

We will perform a chi-square test of independence to assess the equality of proportions across the three language groups since we have bivariate, discrete data.

We will use a significance level of 0.05

Data:

In [162]:
# Test independence for conversion and preferred language
pd.crosstab(df['converted'], df['language_preferred'])
Out[162]:
language_preferred English French Spanish
converted
no 11 19 16
yes 21 15 18
In [163]:
converted_eng = 21/32
converted_fre = 15/34
converted_spa = 18/34

print('Conversion Rate for English:', converted_eng)
print('Conversion Rate for French:', converted_fre)
print('Conversion Rate for Spanish:', converted_spa)

Conversion Rate for English: 0.65625
Conversion Rate for French: 0.4411764705882353
Conversion Rate for Spanish: 0.5294117647058824
In [164]:
# Chi square test for independence
chi2, p, dof, expected = stats.chi2_contingency(pd.crosstab(df['converted'], df['language_preferred']))
print('P Value:', p)

P Value: 0.21298887487543447

Our p value is greater than our alpha (0.05) so we fail to reject the null hypothesis. Although the conversion rate differs for each group, there is not enough statistical evidence to show association with preferred language and conversion rate.

4. Is the time spent on the new page same for the different language users?¶

In [165]:
# visual new_df time spent and language
sns.boxplot(data=new_df, x='language_preferred', y='time_spent_on_the_page', hue='language_preferred')
Out[165]:
<Axes: xlabel='language_preferred', ylabel='time_spent_on_the_page'>

$H_0$ : Average time spent on the new page is the same for different preferred languages.
$H_a$ : At least one of the averages for time spent on the new page is not the same across different preferred languages .

Since we have bivariate data, with discrete and continuous variables, we can use a one-way ANOVA F-Test

We will use a 0.05 level of significance

Gathering Data:

In [166]:
# For new_df show stats for language preferred and time spent

In [167]:
# arrays of time spent by language preferred in new_df
eng_newtime = new_df[new_df['language_preferred'] == 'English']['time_spent_on_the_page']
fre_newtime = new_df[new_df['language_preferred'] == 'French']['time_spent_on_the_page']
spa_newtime = new_df[new_df['language_preferred'] == 'Spanish']['time_spent_on_the_page']
In [168]:
# One-way anova test
stats.f_oneway(eng_newtime, fre_newtime, spa_newtime)
Out[168]:
F_onewayResult(statistic=0.8543992770006822, pvalue=0.43204138694325955)

The p value is 0.43 which is greater than our alpha value of 0.05, so we fail to reject the null hypothesis.

We do not have enough statistical evidence to say that time spent on the new page is different among the preferred language groups.

Conclusion and Business Recommendations¶

  1. At a 5% significance level, we can say that users spend more time on the new landing page than the existing landing page.

  2. Also, at 5% significance we can conclude the conversion rate for the new page is greater than the conversion rate for the old page.

  3. We do not have enough statistical evidence to say that conversion rate and preferred language are associated.

  4. We do not have enough statistical evidence to say that time spent on the new page is different among the preferred language groups.

*Recommendation: Through statistical and bivariate analysis, we have evidence to strongly recommend using the new page over the existing page. We have also shown with 95% confidence that this improves conversion rate and will drive business forward.

Also, it is worth noting that for this random sample the conversion rate with the new page was 0.66 versus a 0.42 conversion rate with the existing page sample. For this dataset, this shows a 57% increase in subscibers for those using the new page.
